<html><head><title>JS fetch() POST over the wire</title></head><body>
<h1>fetch() POST live test</h1>
<p>This page's &lt;script&gt; calls the JavaScript <b>fetch()</b> builtin with
{method:'POST', body:'&lt;token&gt;'} against an ECHO endpoint on the host HTTP
server. On device the engine's fetch() transport routes a POST through the kernel
http9 client's http_post (Plan-9 /net; no sockets), which writes a real POST
request line + Content-Type + Content-Length + body onto the wire. The server
echoes the received body back; hambrowse mirrors the JS console (with the echoed
body) to the serial log as a guest marker.</p>
<script>
fetch("__POST_URL__", {
  method: "POST",
  body: "__TOKEN__",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "text/plain" }
}).then(function (r) {
  return r.text().then(function (t) {
    console.log("HAMPOST status=" + r.status + " ok=" + r.ok + " ct=" +
                r.headers.get("content-type") + " echo=[" + t + "]");
  });
}).catch(function (e) {
  console.log("HAMPOST ERROR " + (e && e.name) + " " + (e && e.message));
});
</script>
</body></html>
